  <div class="nav-group-title">Negative</div>
  <button class="nav-btn neg" data-panel="neg-cx">NEG CX Questions</button>
  <button class="nav-btn neg" data-panel="neg-defense">NEG Defense</button>
  <button class="nav-btn neg" data-panel="neg-rebuttal">NEG Rebuttal Templates</button>

  <div class="nav-group-title">Round Tools</div>
  <button class="nav-btn" data-panel="scouting">Opponent Scouting</button>
  <button class="nav-btn" data-panel="flow">Flow Notes</button>
  <button class="nav-btn" data-panel="matchups">Matchup Map</button>
  <button class="nav-btn" data-panel="about">About / Help</button>
</nav>

<!-- ====================== CONTENT ====================== -->
<main id="content">

<!-- =============== TIMERS =============== -->
<section class="panel active" id="panel-timers">
  <h2>Timers</h2>
  <p>Two timers: prep time (counts down from 4:00) and speech timer (preset buttons for each speech length). Both work offline. Browser must stay open.</p>

  <div class="timers">
    <div class="timer-card">
      <div class="timer-label">Prep Time (4:00 total)</div>
      <div class="timer-display" id="prep-display">4:00</div>
      <div class="timer-controls">
        <button id="prep-start" class="primary">Start</button>
        <button id="prep-pause">Pause</button>
        <button id="prep-reset">Reset 4:00</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="timer-card">
      <div class="timer-label">Speech Timer</div>
      <div class="timer-display" id="speech-display">0:00</div>
      <div class="timer-controls">
        <button id="speech-start" class="primary">Start</button>
        <button id="speech-pause">Pause</button>
        <button id="speech-reset">Reset</button>
      </div>
      <div class="preset-row">
        <button data-seconds="360">AC (6:00)</button>
        <button data-seconds="180">NCX (3:00)</button>
        <button data-seconds="420">NC (7:00)</button>
        <button data-seconds="180">ACX (3:00)</button>
        <button data-seconds="240">1AR (4:00)</button>
        <button data-seconds="360">NR (6:00)</button>
        <button data-seconds="180">2AR (3:00)</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="intro-box">
    Tip: Click the preset button BEFORE you start speaking — the display will show the target, not a countdown. Then hit Start. Display turns orange at 30 seconds left and red at 10 seconds.
  </div>
</section>

<!-- =============== AFF CX =============== -->
<section class="panel" id="panel-aff-cx">
  <h2>AFF CX — Questions to ask NEG</h2>
  <p>Click to expand each question. Plan your follow-ups before the round, then listen to what they actually say.</p>

  <div class="card aff">
    <div class="card-head">Q1: "Do you believe the American Revolution was a just response to British oppression?"</div>
    <div class="card-body">
      <p><span class="label tip">IF YES</span> "Then you've conceded violent revolution can be a just response. The debate is over — you just have to vote AFF." Make this a voter.</p>
      <p><span class="label trap">IF NO</span> "So the founding of the United States was unjust?" Let them sit with it. Most judges will be uncomfortable with this answer.</p>
      <p><span class="label">IF EQUIVOCATING</span> "Different how?" Press. They usually say it was a war of independence, not a revolution. Then ask: "Was British colonial rule political oppression?" If yes → you win. If no → they've defined colonial rule as non-oppression.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card aff">
    <div class="card-head">Q2: "When peaceful protesters are being killed by their government, what should they do?"</div>
    <div class="card-body">
      <p><span class="label trap">IF "KEEP PROTESTING"</span> "So they should keep dying?" Make this concrete with Myanmar: 6,000 civilians killed.</p>
      <p><span class="label">IF "FLEE / OUTSIDE HELP"</span> "What if neither is possible? The Warsaw Ghetto couldn't flee and had no outside help." Trap with Warsaw.</p>
      <p><span class="label tip">IF THEY NAME ANY ALTERNATIVE</span> "Does that work when the regime is willing to massacre civilians?" Force concession that some cases are extreme.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card aff">
    <div class="card-head">Q3: "Do individuals have a right to self-defense against lethal attack?"</div>
    <div class="card-body">
      <p><span class="label tip">IF YES</span> "Does that right disappear when the attacker is a government?" Press. No real moral difference.</p>
      <p><span class="label trap">IF NO</span> You've won. No judge will vote for someone denying the right of self-defense.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card aff">
    <div class="card-head">Q4 (vs. Chenoweth): "Does Chenoweth's 2020 paper show nonviolence is declining in effectiveness?"</div>
    <div class="card-body">
      <p><span class="label tip">IF YES</span> "So your best evidence concedes its own limits. My position doesn't need statistical certainty — it needs one case where violent revolution is justified."</p>
      <p><span class="label">IF NO / THEY'RE UNSURE</span> They haven't read the update. You now have more credibility with flow judges on the methodology.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card aff">
    <div class="card-head">Q5 (vs. Moral Consistency): "Is it ever moral to let innocent people die when you could protect them?"</div>
    <div class="card-body">
      <p><span class="label tip">IF NO</span> "Then when nonviolent resistance cannot protect people being massacred, isn't violent defense a moral obligation?"</p>
      <p><span class="label">IF YES</span> Their "moral consistency" is consistency in accepting deaths. Flip it.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- =============== AFF DEFENSE =============== -->
<section class="panel" id="panel-aff-defense">
  <h2>AFF Defense — Answers to hard NCX questions</h2>
  <p>The NCX is 3:00. NEG will target your weakest points. Prepared answers for the hardest ones.</p>

  <div class="card aff">
    <div class="card-head">"Chenoweth's data proves nonviolence works twice as often."</div>
    <div class="card-body">
      <p><strong>You answer:</strong> "Chenoweth's 2020 paper says that advantage is shrinking — both violent and nonviolent resistance are declining since 2010. Her dataset also excludes the Warsaw Ghetto, which everyone agrees was justified violent resistance. And we're not debating whether nonviolence is usually better. We're debating whether violent revolution is <em>ever</em> a just response. One case is enough."</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card aff">
    <div class="card-head">"Violent revolutions produce new dictators — Russia, Iran, France."</div>
    <div class="card-body">
      <p><strong>You answer:</strong> "I don't defend every violent revolution. I defend revolutions that meet my conditions — a long train of abuses, no lawful remedy. The Warsaw Ghetto wasn't about building a new regime. Myanmar's PDFs protect civilians. The American Revolution produced a democracy. The Haitian Revolution ended slavery. Bad outcomes in some cases don't prove all."</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card aff">
    <div class="card-head">"You can't defend the Reign of Terror."</div>
    <div class="card-body">
      <p><strong>You answer:</strong> "I don't have to. The Reign of Terror was a revolutionary regime purging internal rivals after the oppressor was gone. My framework defends revolution as a response to <em>oppression</em>. The Terror wasn't that — it was internal factional violence. My framework excludes it."</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card aff">
    <div class="card-head">"The American Revolution was unique — can't generalize from it."</div>
    <div class="card-body">
      <p><strong>You answer:</strong> "I'm not generalizing. I'm using it as proof that violent revolution CAN be just. The resolution asks whether it IS a just response, and one clear case settles it. My opponent needs to argue the American Revolution was unjust — a position no judge will accept."</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card aff">
    <div class="card-head">"The means shape the ends — violence produces violent societies."</div>
    <div class="card-body">
      <p><strong>You answer:</strong> "If means shape ends, consider the society produced by accepting oppression. Sudan's peaceful revolution didn't dismantle the institutions of violence — 150,000 are dead. Means don't just shape ends; ends also shape means. Sometimes you have to use force to stop worse force. That's the logic of self-defense at every level."</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card aff">
    <div class="card-head">"Myanmar isn't over — outcome is uncertain."</div>
    <div class="card-body">
      <p><strong>You answer:</strong> "Agreed that Myanmar isn't resolved. But the moral question is about what was justified at the time, not what eventually happens. When the Tatmadaw was slaughtering civilians and only armed resistance could protect them, armed resistance was justified. Full stop. The outcome years later doesn't retroactively delete that moral reality."</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- =============== AFF REBUTTAL =============== -->
<section class="panel" id="panel-aff-rebuttal">
  <h2>AFF Rebuttal Templates</h2>

  <h3>1AR template (4:00) — generic</h3>
  <div class="rebuttal-grid">
    <div class="row header">
      <div>Time</div>
      <div>Task</div>
      <div>What to do</div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
      <div class="time">0:00–0:30</div>
      <div>Framework</div>
      <div>Extend your V and VC. ONE reason yours is superior. 30 seconds, no more.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
      <div class="time">0:30–1:45</div>
      <div>Answer NC</div>
      <div>Go down their case line-by-line. Group where you can. Turns + defense.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
      <div class="time">1:45–3:15</div>
      <div>Extend AC</div>
      <div>Extend your contentions, answer their attacks on each. Biggest block.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
      <div class="time">3:15–4:00</div>
      <div>Voters + weighing</div>
      <div>2-3 reasons to vote AFF. Compare your impacts to theirs directly.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>1AR for Locke vs. Chenoweth</h3>
  <div class="rebuttal-grid">
    <div class="row header"><div>Time</div><div>Move</div><div>Content</div></div>
    <div class="row"><div class="time">0:00–0:30</div><div>Extend framework</div><div>Justice + Social Contract. "Just" = permissible, not optimal.</div></div>
    <div class="row"><div class="time">0:30–1:30</div><div>Attack Chenoweth</div><div>2020 update; dataset exclusions; statistics don't settle rights questions.</div></div>
    <div class="row"><div class="time">1:30–3:15</div><div>Extend AC</div><div>Extend Locke, American Revolution, high-bar conditions. Names and dates.</div></div>
    <div class="row"><div class="time">3:15–4:00</div><div>Weigh</div><div>"Lockean framework precedes and explains when any response is just, including the nonviolent ones."</div></div>
  </div>

  <h3>1AR for Self-Defense vs. King-Gandhi</h3>
  <div class="rebuttal-grid">
    <div class="row header"><div>Time</div><div>Move</div><div>Content</div></div>
    <div class="row"><div class="time">0:00–0:30</div><div>Extend framework</div><div>Human Dignity + Protection of Innocent Life.</div></div>
    <div class="row"><div class="time">0:30–1:45</div><div>Attack King-Gandhi</div><div>Framework asks oppressed to die peacefully. Concrete: Myanmar, Warsaw.</div></div>
    <div class="row"><div class="time">1:45–3:15</div><div>Extend AC</div><div>6,000 killed, 2.7M displaced, 60% liberated. Warsaw Ghetto. Sudan as AFF peg.</div></div>
    <div class="row"><div class="time">3:15–4:00</div><div>Emotional weigh</div><div>"Kyal Sin did not need moral consistency. She needed protection."</div></div>
  </div>

  <h3>2AR template (3:00)</h3>
  <div class="rebuttal-grid">
    <div class="row header"><div>Time</div><div>Task</div><div>What to do</div></div>
    <div class="row"><div class="time">0:00–0:30</div><div>Frame</div><div>ONE sentence why AFF wins.</div></div>
    <div class="row"><div class="time">0:30–1:30</div><div>Extend through NR</div><div>2-3 AC arguments that survived NR. Extend them.</div></div>
    <div class="row"><div class="time">1:30–2:15</div><div>Weigh</div><div>Direct comparison. Your best argument vs. theirs. Why yours wins.</div></div>
    <div class="row"><div class="time">2:15–3:00</div><div>Voters + close</div><div>Clean voters. Call for ballot. Last memory.</div></div>
  </div>
